  ('standing-medicine-ball-scoop-toss', 'Throwing is a linked kinetic-chain skill. Standing Medicine Ball Scoop Toss targets a piece of that chain so the athlete can create force, transfer force, decelerate, or maintain joint position without relying only on the arm.', 'Belongs in Output because the primary adaptation is high-intent power or speed. Use full recovery, low total volume, and stop before ball speed, posture, or release quality drops.', 'Use on throwing or lifting days only when it supports the main goal. Keep high-intent work early and fresh; place strength after skill/output unless it is the primary training block; use resilience work after main throwing or in lower-intensity support sessions.', 'Do not chase fatigue, heavy ball load, or max volume. If throws slow down, release gets wild, landings get loud, or the athlete grimaces, end the set.', 'Regress range, load, speed, distance, partner pressure, cue complexity, or total reps before removing quality. Progress only after the athlete owns pain-free mechanics and recovery between reps.'),
